# Lazy Loading

## Rules

- **Use `React.lazy()` for all route-level components.** Every page/route component should be lazily loaded to split the bundle by route.
- **Use `React.lazy()` for modals and dialogs.** Modal content is not needed until the user opens the modal, so it should be split into a separate chunk.
- **Use `React.lazy()` for heavy components.** Components that import large libraries (charts, rich text editors, date pickers with complex logic) should be lazily loaded.
- **Always wrap lazy components with `<Suspense>`.** Provide a meaningful fallback UI (skeleton, spinner) that matches the layout of the component being loaded.
- **Use named exports with a re-export pattern.** React.lazy() only works with default exports. Use a re-export file to bridge named exports to default exports.
- **Place Suspense boundaries strategically.** Put them at the route level in the router config and at the usage site for modals/heavy components. Do not wrap the entire app in a single Suspense boundary.
- **Preload critical lazy components** on hover or route prefetch to reduce perceived loading time when possible.
- **Do not lazy-load small components** that are always visible or are part of the initial render. Lazy loading adds overhead for tiny components.

## Examples

### Good

```typescript
// Route-level lazy loading in router config
import { lazy, Suspense } from 'react';
import { PageSkeleton } from '@/shared/components/skeletons/page-skeleton';

const DashboardPage = lazy(() =>
  import('@/modules/dashboard/components/dashboard-page').then((m) => ({
    default: m.DashboardPage,
  }))
);

const SettingsPage = lazy(() =>
  import('@/modules/settings/components/settings-page').then((m) => ({
    default: m.SettingsPage,
  }))
);

// In router configuration
const routes = [
  {
    path: '/dashboard',
    element: (
      <Suspense fallback={<PageSkeleton />}>
        <DashboardPage />
      </Suspense>
    ),
  },
  {
    path: '/settings',
    element: (
      <Suspense fallback={<PageSkeleton />}>
        <SettingsPage />
      </Suspense>
    ),
  },
];

// Lazy-loaded modal
const UserFormDialog = lazy(() =>
  import('./user-form-dialog').then((m) => ({ default: m.UserFormDialog }))
);

export const UserList = () => {
  const [isOpen, setIsOpen] = useState(false);

  return (
    <>
      <Button onClick={() => setIsOpen(true)}>{t('users.add')}</Button>
      {isOpen && (
        <Suspense fallback={<DialogSkeleton />}>
          <UserFormDialog open={isOpen} onClose={() => setIsOpen(false)} />
        </Suspense>
      )}
    </>
  );
};

// Lazy-loaded heavy component (chart library)
const RevenueChart = lazy(() =>
  import('./revenue-chart').then((m) => ({ default: m.RevenueChart }))
);

<Suspense fallback={<Skeleton className="h-64 w-full" />}>
  <RevenueChart data={revenueData} />
</Suspense>
```

### Bad

```typescript
// Eagerly importing route-level components
import { DashboardPage } from '@/modules/dashboard/components/dashboard-page';
import { SettingsPage } from '@/modules/settings/components/settings-page';

// Lazy without Suspense
const Page = lazy(() => import('./page'));
<Page /> // No Suspense boundary - will throw if not caught above

// Lazy-loading tiny components
const SmallBadge = lazy(() => import('./badge')); // Too small to benefit

// Single Suspense for entire app
<Suspense fallback={<Spinner />}>
  <App /> {/* Too broad - everything shows spinner on any lazy load */}
</Suspense>

// Using default exports in source files (antipattern for this project)
// my-component.tsx
export default function MyComponent() { ... } // Project uses named exports
```
